Colorectal cancer screening in IBD - can characterization of GI microbiome signatures enhance neoplasia detection?
In recent years, the discovery of disease-specific microbiome signatures for both IBD and CRC has begun to emerge, suggesting that stool-based biomarker detection using metagenomics and other culture-independent technologies may be useful for personalized, early, non-invasive CRC screening in IBD patients. Here we discuss the utility of the stool microbiome as a non-invasive CRC screening tool. Comparing the performance of multiple microbiome-based CRC classifiers, including several multi-cohort meta-analyses, we find that non-invasive detection of colorectal adenomas and carcinomas from microbial biomarkers is an active area of study with promising early results.
